WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.880
 So now we're gonna take a look at the kind of Python code we can write to manipulate these data models.

00:00:05.880 --> 00:00:10.080
 So to do this, we're gonna use what I call the Django shell.

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:13.220
 Now the Django shell looks a lot like the Python shell,

00:00:13.220 --> 00:00:15.240
 except that there's a whole bunch of stuff preloaded.

00:00:15.240 --> 00:00:19.240
 You can't just run Python 3 in interactive mode.

00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:20.800
 You see the chef run prompt.

00:00:20.800 --> 00:00:22.440
 On Linux you see a bracket prompt.

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:24.640
 It's the same shell.

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:30.220
 But in the Django shell, what happens is it actually reads the settings.py and

00:00:30.220 --> 00:00:33.520
 goes and finds all the applications in settings.py and

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:36.760
 preloads the applications and then gives you a shell.

00:00:36.760 --> 00:00:41.880
 So it's like there's a bunch of things that happen that's not just a shell that

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:43.780
 are done before you're in the shell.

00:00:43.780 --> 00:00:48.600
 And this statement of from book one models import book lang instance,

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:51.880
 that wouldn't work if you just ran the Python shell by itself.

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:59.520
 That's because the book one application was loaded by python3manage.py shell.

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:02.560
 After that, you've got all these things preloaded, but

00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:05.360
 then you can pretty much run any Python that you want.

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:10.040
 That messes with all of your Django classes and objects, etc, etc.

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:13.600
 So let's take a look at the kinds of things that we can do.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:18.560
 So if you remember, our data model was named lang for language.

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:23.540
 And so we can create a new object in memory with lang parenthesis name equals

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:25.120
 quote en quote.

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:29.120
 And that basically says give me a new language object and

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:34.000
 set the attribute name to be en.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.480
 And give that to me back in a variable.

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:38.840
 That's an object oriented constructor.

00:01:38.840 --> 00:01:40.480
 We're constructing an object.

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:42.200
 Now that doesn't store it in the database.

00:01:42.200 --> 00:01:45.160
 That simply creates it in memory and gives it back.

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:48.480
 So it's a Python object with a attribute.

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:49.400
 It knows it's a language.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:54.260
 Now the save method, z.save, that is the thing that says, you know what,

00:01:54.260 --> 00:01:57.360
 I've got this thing in memory, please persist it to the database.

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:01.240
 Write it, transmit it to the database, and come back.

00:02:01.240 --> 00:02:05.960
 Now what's cool about that is this ID column, that's been set at that moment.

00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:09.040
 So we can say, what ID did we get?

00:02:09.040 --> 00:02:13.320
 So remember how every row that we put in a model gets an ID value.

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:16.680
 And we're gonna use that ID value as the handle to point to.

00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:21.880
 So this is the primary key, which is the way we point to a row in a table.

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:25.120
 So then what we can do is we can make a book, right?

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:26.680
 So we made a language.

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:29.120
 We made a language, and we know what its ID is.

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:32.960
 Now we're gonna make a book, and it's got like a title and an ISBN.

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:36.360
 And what we do is we say, and the language is z.

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:38.480
 Now z there is that variable.

00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:43.800
 Now we don't use the ID, Django knows all about how IDs work.

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:47.440
 And so it knows when you're saying lang = z, that it's gonna make a lang ID and

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:50.840
 put the ID of the language row in.

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:52.760
 Foreign key, all this stuff's just done.

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:57.680
 You just have to have a variable that has an ID value and pass that in.

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:00.640
 So what that's doing is that is making a book and

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:03.840
 then connecting it to a lang, right?

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:07.360
 Now that's also not saved until you've saved the book.

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:09.120
 The book is now transmitted to the database.

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:10.960
 It has a foreign key in it.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:12.440
 It gets its own primary key.

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:14.680
 So it's primary, it's the first book that we've inserted.

00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:18.440
 So its primary key x.id is 1.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:21.440
 And then we can make an instance.

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:25.360
 And the instance needs a do back, which is a date.

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:27.680
 And then it needs which book it is.

00:03:27.680 --> 00:03:32.160
 And we use that variable x to indicate which book that we're talking about.

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:36.160
 So that's just creating a link from the book instance in memory

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:38.400
 that we get back in the variable a.

00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:42.120
 It's a book instance that points to the book that's in the variable x,

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:45.720
 which is pyfree, isbn42.

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:52.040
 And then we save that, And that has an ID.

00:03:52.040 --> 00:03:55.080
 So now we have created a language record.

00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:57.800
 Then we created a book record that linked to the language record.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:02.920
 And then we created a book instance record that linked to the book record, okay?

00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:08.720
 And so that is this whole linking thing, right?

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:10.200
 So these are the pointers.

00:04:10.200 --> 00:04:16.080
 And what Django's doing in this situation is Django's trying to hide from us

00:04:16.080 --> 00:04:18.640
 the whole idea of the foreign keys and the primary keys,

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:22.840
 other than me asking what the ID is, it's not really something you have to do.

00:04:22.840 --> 00:04:24.880
 So all those asking for the IDs aren't necessary.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:28.600
 You just say, look, I have a book and its language is this thing.

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:29.960
 I don't know what its ID is.

00:04:29.960 --> 00:04:33.120
 You should please make me a column and do all this magic stuff.

00:04:33.120 --> 00:04:36.840
 So, so much of the bookkeeping of these one to many relationships or

00:04:36.840 --> 00:04:41.480
 foreign key relationships in general, in Django is just done automatically.

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:46.680
 Now, we can retrieve these and we can sort of walk down these things,

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:47.700
 walk through these things.

00:04:47.700 --> 00:04:52.800
 So here we are again in samples and we run the shell and we import our models.

00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:58.920
 And we can say book.objects and book is a class from our models.

00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:05.720
 It's book1.models.book and then a lot of the methods that we talk to

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:09.520
 inside of these classes are under the attribute.objects.

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:13.080
 Which is, you could think of it as all of the rows in a sense, or

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:17.960
 all the objects in this model, all the rows in the table that lives there.

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:21.600
 Book objects and then get is like which one do you want?

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:24.960
 Get pk=1, pk means primary key.

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:27.840
 I don't know, I think it would make more sense if we called this ID.

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:32.880
 But ID is the name of the column of the primary key is really just kind of

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:36.480
 like a convention that's done 98% of the time.

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:41.160
 It's not required, it's not the truth, but it's so common that it might as well be.

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:47.360
 But pk really means primary key, which 9 out of 10 times is the column ID.

00:05:47.360 --> 00:05:51.200
 So we're loading from the books table, we're pulling that in.

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:54.680
 And we're getting the row number 1 from the books table.

00:05:54.680 --> 00:06:00.480
 So if you say what the title is, well, the title of that is Py4e.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:03.680
 Now, there's a title, but then there's lang.

00:06:03.680 --> 00:06:07.800
 Lang is that foreign key that points to the language.

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:12.160
 And so we can say x.lang, that is the entire language row.

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:16.280
 But x.lang.name is within that row, it's the name column.

00:06:16.280 --> 00:06:19.080
 So we sort of walk down the little arrow and

00:06:19.080 --> 00:06:21.160
 grab one of the elements out of that.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:26.140
 So it's like walking from a book to the corresponding language row and

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:28.440
 then pulling the name out of that corresponding language row.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:31.040
 So I think that's a really pretty syntax.

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:36.160
 And it starts to make sense after a while, you walk through the little arrows.

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:41.720
 And this is why the picture of the data model is so absolutely important, oops.

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:47.280
 And so now we're gonna go grab the book instance number 1,

00:06:47.280 --> 00:06:49.920
 the first row of the book instance table.

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:54.320
 So instance.objects get pk equals 1, that says give me that first row,

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:56.440
 give it back to me in the variable y.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:06:59.400
 What is the do back of this one, and then you can sort of walk it.

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:03.960
 You can say, I'm at a book instance, and I wanna follow the foreign key to

00:07:03.960 --> 00:07:08.920
 the book table to get me a book, and then give me the title of that book, right?

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:11.880
 So from a book instance, you can walk to the book table and

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:15.640
 then get the title of the book, and then we get py free.

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:19.840
 So you see this sort of starting from one row,

00:07:19.840 --> 00:07:26.160
 walking to another corresponding row that's pointed to by this relationship.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:28.720
 And that's the essence of this.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:30.200
 We're gonna do this a whole bunch.

00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:34.520
 By the time we come back to this, this will all seem pretty straightforward.

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:44.520
 [MUSIC]

